    {
      "turn_number": 32,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "I keep thinking about all the little things that never got said. Like the way my doctor wrote “lack of transportation” in my chart once—like that one line explains everything—but she never asked how I actually get here, who I’ve asked for rides, or if I’m eating enough between shifts. I scroll my phone at night reading about babies’ gut microbiomes and convince myself I’m ruining him because we can only afford frozen dinners. I’m terrified of a C‑section not because of the surgery alone but because I worry he’ll miss the “good” bacteria everyone talks about. I want to ask about stress and his immune system, but I choke up and say I’m fine.\n\nSometimes I imagine someone from the clinic calling to say, “We’ll come by,” or a midwife who knows my name and my schedule. Instead, I feel like a number at appointments, rushed, left figuring out rides with neighbors. I’m grateful my husband is working so hard, but I hate feeling like a burden asking him to rearrange shifts. I don’t have answers—just a lot of fear, some hope, and a wish that someone would see me as more than a file.",
      "responding_to_question_id": "Q15",
      "input_tokens": 1460,
      "output_tokens": 506
    },
